Date: Wed, 10 Sep 2003 08:27:14 -0500
From: Richard A. Nisbett <richard.a.nisbett@ttu.edu>

While I am not the authoritative source you sought regarding this posting,
I can offer an anecdotal account of being on mefloquine prophylaxis during
one of my annual trips to work in Liberia and returning to the US with
falciparum malaria in March 2000.
Following treatment, I did an exhaustive search for any reports concerning
mefloquine resistance in the Upper Guinea subregion and did find a single
report listing Liberia. Unfortunately, the only citation presently at my
fingertips suggests the existence of mefloquine-resistant falciparum
malaria only in adjacent Sierra Leone and Cote d'Ivoire as well as Burkina
Faso in late 1988 (Raccurt CP et al. 1991).
Given the sub-region's complex emergency that began in late December 1989
in Liberia, the collapsed health infrastructure since then, the porous
borders, and geopolitical entanglements among the various warring factions
still active in the subregion, the issue of mefloquine resistance is an
important and interesting topic. I too encourage an authoritative source to
provide us with more details.
Citation: Raccurt CP, Dumestre-Toulet V, Abraham E, Le Bras M,
Brachet-Liermain, A, Ripert C (1991). Failure of falciparum malaria
prophylaxis by mefloquine in travelers from West Africa. Am. J Trop Med
Hyg. Sept; 45(3):319-24.
--
