[3]
Date: 10 Sep 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: ABC news [edited]
<http://abcnews.go.com/wire/Politics/ap20030910_851.html>

More Marines Get Malaria Symptoms After Liberia Mission; Doctors Investigating
----------------------
Navy doctors are investigating what they say is an unusually high rate of
malaria among Marines who were in Liberia last month on a peacekeeping mission.
3 more patients turned up with symptoms and are being treated aboard the
USS Iwo Jima off the West African coast, bringing the number ill Wednesday
to 46, said Master Sgt. John V. Tomassi of the U.S. European Command.
That represents some 20 percent of 225 Marines and Navy personnel who went
ashore last month, a surprising number since the anti-malarial drug they
were given is normally highly effective in preventing the mosquito-born
illness. The number of confirmed cases among the 46 now stands at 18, up
from 13 Tuesday, Tomassi said.
Doctors are closely watching the rest of some 225 who went ashore, an
unknown number of whom also are reported to have complained of body aches,
one of the symptoms, said Capt. Greg Martin of the National Naval Medical
Center in Bethesda, Md.
"There are a lot of questions about this," he told a press conference
Tuesday in the Washington suburb of Bethesda, where most of the patients
were taken.
Doctors are looking into 3 possibilities for the outbreak, he said: The
strain of malaria troops got has become resistant to the drug they were
taking; troops didn't take it correctly; the drug had gone bad, or there
was a flaw in its manufacture. All going ashore are being switched to
another antimalarial in case resistance is the problem, doctors said.
The 3 new patients remaining aboard ship are a Marine, an Army soldier, and
a civilian.
Previously, 43 Marines and sailors with more serious cases had been
evacuated from their ships for hospitalization. They all had gone ashore in
Liberia from the amphibious assault ship USS Iwo Jima and the amphibious
landing dock USS Carter Hall, officials said.
5 of those evacuated have serious cases, including 2 patients with cerebral
malaria. But all are expected to recover, said Lt. Cmdr. David Blazes, a
doctor who specializes in infectious disease and is caring for those
brought to Bethesda.
Martin said the Marines and sailors started taking the antimalarial drug
mefloquine in late June or early July 2003 in a regimen that requires
troops to begin dosing 2 weeks in advance of a deployment, then take the
drug weekly thereafter until they have been out of the risk area for a month.
The military also gives troops a repellent cream containing DEET and
mosquito netting.
Col. Jay DeFrank, a Defense Department spokesman, said the Marines, members
of the 26th Marine Expeditionary Unit based at Camp Lejeune, N.C., were in
Liberia in mid-August as part of a U.S. quick-reaction force of about 150
troops. They operated from an airport outside Monrovia, the capital, for
about 10 days. Others went back and forth from the ships to land, sometimes
for as little as a couple of hours at a time.
Doctors said they are asking the patients whether they took their drugs
faithfully, whether they slept inside or out at night, and other pertinent
questions.
Of the 43 evacuated to hospitals, 41 were taken to Bethesda and 2 to the
Landstuhl Regional Medical Center in Germany in the flights that began over
the weekend.
Officials said that as a precaution, movements of Marines ashore in Liberia
from the Iwo Jima, Carter Hall, and another ship off the Liberian coast
were being limited for the time being. About 136 American troops still are
ashore in Liberia, mostly Marines providing security at the U.S. Embassy in
Monrovia. The Iwo Jima and 2 other ships off the coast carry about 2200
Marines and about 2500 sailors.
Malaria is transmitted by mosquitos, which breed in stagnant water.
The disease infects 300 million people a year and kills at least 1 million
in Africa and elsewhere and has become increasingly resistant to drugs,
according to the World Health Organization and the United Nations
Children's Fund, UNICEF. Some 3000 African children die every day from it,
the United Nations said in a report early in 2003.
About 800 American civilians come home with malaria each year from trips
abroad, according to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.
The malaria parasite has developed resistance to the old standby drug,
chloroquine, in most of the world, rendering that drug largely useless and
leaving only mefloquine and 2 others.
Large areas of Central and South America, the Dominican Republic and Haiti,
the Indian subcontinent, Southeast Asia, the Middle East, and Oceania also
are considered malaria-risk areas, according to the CDC.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[As mentioned in the earlier posting on this observed outbreak of malaria
in USA troops in Liberia, it is clear that there has been a failure of
chemoprophylaxis. The question that remains is whether the failure
resulted from individuals non-compliant with recommended chemoprophylaxis
or actual failure of the chemoprophylaxis drug itself, either through
development of drug resistance on the part of the parasite, poor absorption
of the drug leading to sub-therapeutic (protective) levels or reduced
quality of drug resulting in a lower effective dose administered. The
newswire reports above seem to suggest that in fact the majority of the
observed cases gave a history of following the recommended chemoprophylaxis
with mefloquine.
Mefloquine resistance has been reported in Southeast Asian countries and in
sub-Saharan African countries. Jelinik, Grobusch and Loscher (see ref. 3)
found in vitro resistance of _Plasmodium falciparum_ in 9.6 percent of
isolates from German travellers returning from sub-Saharan African
countries. Lobel et al. (ref.4) documented 5 out of 15 prophylaxis failures
with mefloquine levels greater than or equal to 620 ng/ml in blood drawn
within 5 days of onset of illness. (Note that the Lobel paper was
published in 1998 -- 5 years ago.)
One wonders whether the recent disruption of health infrastructure in
Liberia may have led to an artificial masking of mefloquine resistance
development in the country -- one that is now coming to light in the face
of a sizable group of malaria-sensitive individuals being exposed in a
short period of time, in a situation analogous to a common source outbreak.
We await further information from authoritative sources on the results of
the investigation into the etiology of this apparent outbreak of
mefloquine-resistant _Plasmodium falciparum_.
1: Wichmann O, Betschart B, Loscher T, Nothdurft HD, Sonnenburg FV,
Jelinek T. Prophylaxis failure due to probable mefloquine resistant P
falciparum from Tanzania. Acta Trop. 2003 Apr;86(1):63-5.
2: Wongsrichanalai C, Pickard AL, Wernsdorfer WH, Meshnick
SR. Epidemiology of drug-resistant malaria. Lancet Infect Dis. 2002
Apr;2(4):209-18.
3: Jelinek T, Grobusch MP, Loscher T. Patterns of Plasmodium falciparum
drug resistance in nonimmune travellers to Africa. Eur J Clin Microbiol
Infect Dis. 2001 Apr;20(4):284-6.
4: Lobel HO, Varma JK, Miani M, Green M, Todd GD, Grady K, Barber
AM. Monitoring for mefloquine-resistant Plasmodium falciparum in Africa:
implications for travelers' health. Am J Trop Med Hyg. 1998 Jul;59(1):129-32.
5: Philipps J, Radloff PD, Wernsdorfer W, Kremsner PG. Follow-up of the
susceptibility of Plasmodium falciparum to antimalarials in Gabon. Am J
Trop Med Hyg. 1998 May;58(5):612-8. - Mod.MPP]
